               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460511-name-1128" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460511-name-1128" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460511-name-1128" type="surname" value="KENT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460511-name-1128" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY KENT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Edward Kent, wine-merchant, Bedford. place, Old Kent-road: the prisoner was in his service. I sent him, on the 2nd of April, for a shin of beef—he went, and brought the young man with him, with the shin of beef, and a note saying it was 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I said I understood it was only 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the prisoner went down, and returned and said that would do—I gave him a half-crown and a sixpence, to give to Mr. Neal's servant, whose name was Paynter.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> When I left she stopped the money for it. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> That was a different concern—he absconded on the 15th of April, before I had found this out—his mother came two days afterwards for his wages—Mr. Kent said he would not pay anybody but Henry—the prisoner came on the Saturday, and we deducted a half-crown that he had absconded with before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460511-name-1129" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460511-name-1129" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
